1. Introduction

Nowadays, having conversations online can be tough. The anonymous factor makes people express themselves much more aggressive than they would in real life. Be on a comment section from a YouTube video, or on a discussion about an article from a newspaper, or online video games, this problem is frequent and platforms have difficulty in dealing with this problem.

The goal of this project is to build a model to detects different types of toxicity like threats, obscenity, insults, and identity hate, based on text data.

5. Bi-grams

The most used words per category might be interesting, and we might find some words that define certain categories. But perhaps the combination of words might be even more determining of the problem.

We can do the same analysis as before, but now we work with pairs of words. We first unnest the training data set, and we follow by removing the pairs that contain stop words.

data_bi<-unnest_tokens(train, bigram, comment_text,token = "ngrams",n=2) #

data_bi<- separate(data_bi,bigram,c("word1","word2"))

data_bi<-
  data_bi %>%
  filter(!(word1 %in% stop_words$word)) %>%
  filter(!(word2 %in% stop_words$word)) %>%
  unite(bigram, word1, word2, sep = " ") %>%
  as.data.table()

6. Sentiment Analysis

Every word has a meaning and it can have a positive or negative interpretation. Each document might have both positive and negative words but if the negative words outweigh the positive, we can expect the presence of some sort of toxicity.

data<-
data %>%
  merge(get_sentiments("bing"), by = "word", all.x = T)%>%
  as.data.table


data[,sentiment:=ifelse(sentiment=='positive',1,-1)]

data[sentiment==-1,SenNeg:=sum(sentiment,na.rm=T),by=id]
data[sentiment==1 ,SenPos:=sum(sentiment,na.rm=T),by=id]

Since weâre dealing with text that does not come strictly from books or magazines, we can expect a lot of grammar mistakes. But most important, we should note that most words have a neuter meaning. For this reason, I expect that the sentiment package will not be able to make a perfect match and not give a value for some words.

100*sum(data[,is.na(sentiment)])/nrow(data)
## [1] 88.21318

Unfortunately we only have a sentiment for 12% of the words present on our text. Nonetheless, we can see how it toxic or not some of the documents are depending on their overall sentiment.

data[,.(sum(sentiment,na.rm = T),inci),by="id"][,mean(V1),by=inci]%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=inci,y=V1))+
  geom_point()+
  labs(x = "Number of Different Problems", y="Average Sentiment")

We expected that the more negative overall a text is, the more problems of toxicity it displays. That is evident for the texts that display all of the problems, but overall we can see that the more negative it is, the more problems.

In fact, we can see the average of texts that display problems and the texts that donât.

7. Feature Engineering

We combine both our data sets in order to derive the necessary features of each text. We clean the text from any character which is not a letter and remove the stop words. This should make our âDocument Term Matrixâ smaller.

data <-
train %>% 
  select(-c(toxic, severe_toxic, obscene, threat, insult, identity_hate)) %>% 
  bind_rows(test)%>%
  mutate(comment_text=gsub("[^a-zA-Z]"," ",comment_text))%>%
  unnest_tokens(word, comment_text)%>%
  anti_join(stop_words,by="word")%>%
  merge(get_sentiments("bing"), by = "word", all.x = T)%>%
  mutate(sentiment=ifelse(sentiment=='positive',1,-1))%>%
  mutate(num_ch=nchar(word))%>%
  as.data.table

The features we add are the number of words in the text, the average length of each word, the maximum character of any word in the text, the overall sentiment of the text, the number of âpositiveâ words, and number of ânegativeâ.

We create these variables in order to add them to our DTM later.

variables<- 
  data[,.(txt_len=.N,
          AverChar=mean(num_ch),
          MaxChar=max(num_ch),
      Sentiment= sum(sentiment,na.rm=T)
        ,SenNeg= sum(sentiment==-1,na.rm=T)
        ,SenPos= sum(sentiment== 1,na.rm=T))
     ,by=id]

8. Document Term Matrix

A document-term matrix is a matrix where each row represents a document and each column a term, and the entries of this matrix represent the number of times each term appears in each document. It is used to describe the frequency of terms per document. We can either use the number of term frequency or the âtf-idfâ, which stands for âterm frequency-inverse document frequencyâ.

We now create the dtm for our collection of texts.

freq <-
  data %>%
  mutate(word=wordStem(word))%>%
  filter(15>num_ch & num_ch>2)%>%
  count(id, word) 

dtm <-
  cast_sparse(freq,id, word, n)
## Warning: Trying to compute distinct() for variables not found in the data:
## - `row_col`, `column_col`
## This is an error, but only a warning is raised for compatibility reasons.
## The operation will return the input unchanged.
dim(dtm);rm(data)
## [1] 246648 198854

We have our âdocument term matrixâ with the frequency of each word for each document. The dimensions of this matrix are the number of documents by the number of unique words in all documents.

Furthermore, we combine the variables we had calculated the chapter before with this matrix.

dtm <-
  cbind(dtm,as.matrix(variables[id %in% freq$id][order(id)]));rm(variables)

Itâs important to point out that thereâs some documents from our initial train and test data sets that do not appear in this matrix. This is because some documents after cleaning and filtering for words with only number of letters between 2 and 15 displayed no words and so we donât use them for training and for prediction we will predict them as not displaying no problems.

For the document number 1 and 20, the variables 5,6,10,12 are:

dtm[c(1,20),c(5,6,10,12)]
## 2 x 4 sparse Matrix of class "dgCMatrix"
##    termin true merwin vandal
## 1       1    1      .      .
## 20      .    .      .      2

9. Model, parameters, XGBOOST

One of the most popular and talked models nowadayson Kaggle has to be the xgBoost (short for âextreme gradient boostingâ) and itâs the one we will use now.

In order to create our predictive models we must first split our matrix into two, corresponding to the train and test data.

subm[ ,id_N:=(nrow(train)+1):(nrow(train)+nrow(test))]
subm_new<-subm[id_N %in% freq$id,] 

index<-c(1:nrow(train[id %in% freq$id]))
X<-dtm[index,]
X_test <-dtm[-index,];rm(dtm)

The main parameter we have to fix is the evaluation metric. For this competition the submissions were evaluated on the mean of the individual AUC(under the curve) of each predicted column.

We can and we had to, tune the parameters in order to achieve a reasonable and satisfying error.

targets <- c("toxic", "severe_toxic", "obscene", "threat", "insult", "identity_hate")

parameters <- list(objective        = "binary:logistic", 
                   booster          = "gbtree", 
                   eval_metric      = "auc", 
                   nthread          = 5, 
                   eta              = 0.2, 
                   max_depth        = 5,
                   min_child_weight = 5,
                   subsample        = 1,
                   colsample_bytree = 0.7)

i=1
for (target in targets) {
  cat("\nFitting", target, "...\n")
  y <- train[id %in% freq$id][[target]]
  m_xgb <- xgboost(X[,!(colnames(X) %in% c("id"))], y, params = parameters, print_every_n = 500, nrounds = 1000)
  
  subm_new[[target]] <-predict(m_xgb, X_test[,!(colnames(X) %in% c("id"))])
  
  assign(paste("f",i,sep=""),as.tibble(xgb.importance(feature_names = colnames(X[,!(colnames(X) %in% c("id"))]), model = m_xgb)))
  i<-i+1
}

12. Conclusion and Future Work

Prior to this project I had no experience working with text data, so this was made with the intent to get myself familiarized with some NLP packages and have some fun.

There are a lot of things I could have tried, like working with td-idf instead of the term frequency for the dtm (document-term matrix), or somehow incorporate a POS-tagger (part-of-speech tagger).

The most important thing to do in my opinion would have been to spend a lot of time on cleaning the text data. I tried to make it cleaner by removing all the non-letter characters and removing the stop words, but thereâs still a lot of grammar mistakes that if corrected, would for sure help with our prediction goal.
